    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:e29dcc50-2218-42ef-9105-cb20b6ad3fcf",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 31-year-old woman who appears mildly uncomfortable and fatigued, shifting often in her seat and crossing her legs as she describes a constant urge to urinate. She is well groomed, casually dressed, and otherwise looks healthy. Over the past three days she has developed burning with urination, urinary frequency, urgency, suprapubic pressure, and passing of only small amounts of urine each time. She says the burning is worst at the end of voiding and that she feels as though she still needs to urinate immediately afterward. She denies flank pain, fever, chills, nausea, or vomiting, but says the discomfort has become distracting enough that she is having trouble concentrating at work. She reports no visible blood in the urine, though she has noticed the urine looks darker and has a stronger odor than usual. She also denies vaginal discharge, vaginal itching, or abnormal bleeding, which makes her feel this is similar to prior bladder infections rather than a vaginal problem.\n\nShe works full time as a marketing coordinator in a busy office and often delays bathroom breaks during long meetings. Her daily routine is hectic, and she admits she sometimes does not drink enough water during the workday, relying instead on coffee to stay alert. She lives with her long-term partner, is sexually active, and notes that her symptoms began about a day after a weekend trip and recent intercourse. For contraception she uses a combined oral contraceptive and often also uses spermicide-coated condoms, especially while traveling, which she has noticed sometimes precedes bladder irritation. She does not smoke, drinks alcohol socially on weekends, and exercises intermittently with yoga classes and light jogging.\n\nAt home, {patientName} is independent in all activities of daily living and has a supportive social network that includes her partner, a close friend group, and nearby family. She enjoys hiking and occasionally goes on long day hikes where she purposefully limits fluids and postpones urination because restroom access is limited; she also likes streaming crime dramas and cooking. During the past two days she has avoided outings because of frequent trips to the bathroom and fear of suddenly needing a restroom. She is worried because she has had similar bladder infections once or twice in the past, and she recognizes the pattern of symptoms.\n\nOn examination, she is alert and oriented, speaking clearly and without respiratory distress. She appears mildly distressed from dysuria but is nontoxic. She has mild suprapubic tenderness without rebound or guarding and no costovertebral angle tenderness. There is no clinical evidence of sepsis or upper urinary tract involvement, and the presentation is most consistent with an uncomplicated lower urinary tract infection."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:228ae469-452d-4069-a209-a70cd18dd932",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has generally been healthy, but she does report chronic constipation and intermittent pelvic floor dysfunction symptoms with occasional sensation of incomplete bladder emptying, especially when she postpones urination for long periods at work. These issues have never required hospitalization or specialist care, but they may contribute to urinary stasis and increase her susceptibility to bladder infections. She recalls two prior uncomplicated urinary tract infections in her twenties, both treated successfully as an outpatient with oral antibiotics. She has never been hospitalized for a urinary infection and has no history of kidney stones, structural urinary tract disease, diabetes, immunocompromise, or recurrent pyelonephritis.\n\nHer past medical history is notable for seasonal allergic rhinitis, occasional tension headaches, and constipation. She takes a combined oral contraceptive regularly, uses cetirizine during allergy season, and uses over-the-counter ibuprofen as needed for menstrual cramps or headaches. She also reports intermittent use of spermicide-coated condoms with her partner, particularly during travel, which is a recognized behavioral and product-related risk factor for cystitis. She reports no current pregnancy and says her last menstrual period was about two weeks ago. She has had no recent urinary catheterization, urologic procedures, or known sexually transmitted infections, and she denies abnormal vaginal discharge, vulvovaginal irritation, or dyspareunia with the current episode.\n\nLifestyle factors relevant to the current illness include intermittent low fluid intake, frequent postponement of urination during work hours, recent sexual activity, and occasional long hikes where she intentionally limits water intake and delays voiding due to poor restroom access. She usually drinks 1-2 cups of coffee on workdays and alcohol socially on weekends. She denies tobacco or recreational drug use. She is up to date on routine primary care and gynecologic screening and has not had recent high fever, rigors, flank pain, vomiting, or severe back pain."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
